Bellman-Ford Algorithm

The Bellman-Ford algorithm is a single-source shortest path algorithm used to find the shortest weighted distance from a starting node (source) to all other nodes in a graph.

Key Advantages:
Unlike Dijkstra's algorithm, Bellman-Ford works accurately on graphs with negative edge weights.
It can detect the presence of negative weight cycles (a cycle whose edges sum to a negative value). 

Complexity:
Time Complexity: O(V * E) (where V is vertices and E is edges).
Space Complexity: O(V) for the distance array.

How it Works (Dynamic Programming Approach) // only for revision purpose not detiled steps
Unlike Dijkstra (which is Greedy), Bellman-Ford uses Dynamic Programming. 
1. We initialize the distance to the source node as 0 and all other nodes to infinity (or a very large number like 1e9).
2. We then relax all edges exactly V-1 times. Relaxing an edge means checking if the distance to a destination node can be shortened by taking a specific edge.
3. After V-1 iterations, the shortest paths are guaranteed to be found if there are no negative cycles.
4. We do one final iteration (the V-th iteration) to check for negative cycles. If any distance updates during this final pass, it proves a negative cycle exists.

Q: Why are we iterating exactly V-1 times? //follow up and important comceptual questions with simple and small explanation
A simple path (a path with no cycles) in a graph with V vertices can have at most V-1 edges. By relaxing all edges V-1 times, we guarantee that shortest paths of all possible lengths (from 1 edge up to V-1 edges) are explored and calculated. Any further iterations are redundant unless a negative weight cycle exists, which would cause the distances to continuously shrink to negative infinity.

Implementation (Standard)

vector<int> bellman_ford(int V, vector<vector<int>>& edges, int S) {
    // Initialize distances to infinity (1e9), and source to 0
    vector<int> result(V, 1e9);
    result[S] = 0;

    // Relax all edges V - 1 times
    for(int cnt = 1; cnt <= V - 1; cnt++) {
        for(auto edge : edges) {
            int u = edge[0];
            int v = edge[1];
            int wt = edge[2];

            // If node 'u' is reachable and the path through 'u' is shorter, update 'v'
            if(result[u] != 1e9 && result[u] + wt < result[v]) {
                result[v] = result[u] + wt;
            } 
        }
    }
    
    // N-th iteration to check for negative weight cycles
    for(auto edge : edges) {
        int u = edge[0];
        int v = edge[1];
        int wt = edge[2];

        if(result[u] != 1e9 && result[u] + wt < result[v]) {
            // A negative cycle is detected
            return {-1}; 
        } 
    }

    return result;
}

Implementation (With Path Tracking) // other imp variations of this algo or topic

If we also need to reconstruct the actual shortest path from the source to any node, we can maintain a parent array. Every time we successfully relax an edge, we update the parent of the destination node.

vector<int> bellman_ford_with_path(int V, vector<vector<int>>& edges, int S, vector<int>& parent) {
    vector<int> result(V, 1e9);
    
    // Resize and initialize parent array to -1
    parent.assign(V, -1); 
    result[S] = 0;

    // Relax all edges V - 1 times
    for(int cnt = 1; cnt <= V - 1; cnt++) {
        for(auto edge : edges) {
            int u = edge[0];
            int v = edge[1];
            int wt = edge[2];

            if(result[u] != 1e9 && result[u] + wt < result[v]) {
                result[v] = result[u] + wt;
                parent[v] = u; // Track the node we came from
            } 
        }
    }
    
    // N-th iteration to check for negative weight cycles
    for(auto edge : edges) {
        int u = edge[0];
        int v = edge[1];
        int wt = edge[2];

        if(result[u] != 1e9 && result[u] + wt < result[v]) {
            return {-1}; // Cycle detected
        } 
    }

    return result;
}
